title: For Sale/Trade:  Mossberg 146B
postcontent:
Mossberg 146B. 22LR - S Bolt Action Rifle in great shape.  The Mossberg 146B was first manufactured in 1949 (it came out with three other models that year all with "T" bolt handles, the 142A, 142M, and 144). It was a refresh of the old model 46B produced from 1938 through 1946 (no production during WWII)... Model number changed in 1954 to 146B-A or 146B(a) then to 146B(b) final production was around 1958.  That puts my gun at between 1949 and 1954.  I have had it since around 1970 when my grandfather gave it to me from his collection.

Here is a link to some information that I found.

http://home.epix.net/~damguy/models.htm

Takedown, 22  lr,l,s, tubular magazine holds 20(lr), 23(l), 30(s).  26" barrel.  Weight 7 lbs.  Plain stock with pistol grip, Monte Carlo comb and cheek-piece, knob for-end tip, swivels.  (146B) No. 1A ramp front sight, No. S107 rear sight, No. S130 receiver sight, Made 1949-1954.  Includes original rear sight loose.  Williams peep site mounted on the rear now.  Includes Weaver 4X scope with view through for iron sights.

title: For Sale:  Romanian M69 Military 22 LR Training Rifles (several to choose from)
postcontent:
I have for sale a pair of Romanian Model 1969 Military 22 LR Training Rifles. These rifles are known for their accuracy and durability. I purchased a few of these back when they were still easily available, intending to finish each one over time. As you can tell by the picture, I've only gotten around to finishing one. Note that the finished one on the bottom is NOT for sale.

While these 22 LR rifles are perfectly shootable "as-is", I recommend you consider these as a project rifle with the following considerations:

1. Magazine Well. Each Romy M69 will come with one 5-round magazine. I have 5 of these rifles and the fitting of the magazine to the mag well has been hit and miss. Some of the receivers have required a bit of modification for the magazines to slide in and out freely.

2. Case Ejection. As is common in these M69's, the cases are not often fully ejected from the ejection port, requiring the shooter to slightly tip the rifle and allow it to fall out. This is "as-designed" in the rifle. One of the only quirks I've come to discover.

3. Scope Rings. The rifles are extremely accurate with the built-in 25, 50 and 100 yard sight adjustments. However, I've heard (but never verified) that mounting a scope can be a challenge.

4. Wood Rifinish. These rifles refinish VERY nicely. As you can tell from the bottom rifle, some have Beech wood, but more commonly Walnut stocks. The fun of these rifles is that they are great project guns, but you aren't going to ruin the collector value by trying your hand at refinishing or reblueing. The stocks are in great shape, but the finish leaves something to be desired. They all refinish beautifully.

5. Bore Condition. Perfect. Nothing really to add here. For that matter, the rifles are free of rust, pitting, etc... They're just a bit dirty and need some TLC in that regard.

title: For Sale:  Springfield Rifles, Some facts
postcontent: 1903 rifles have Straight grip stocks with finger grooves, 03A3 rifles have striaght grip, scant grip, and C stock grip, ie. Pistol Grip. the only serial numbered parts on rifle were the receivers with the exception of National Match rifles which had the bolts electro pencilied with the receiver number. Polished bolts marked NS for nickel steel were standard on NM rifles and some were fitted with C stocks also, early triggers were grooved, bolts body's were smooth and had a bolt handle that was forged staight down, later designs are swept slightly to the rear. rear sights were mounted on a collar press fitted to the barrels which also contained the sight base, the windage markings and the semi circle gearing for the rear sight windage adjustment, the sight has two options, when folded down the groove in sight is set for 550 yards, the battle sight setting. when the site is raised up you have both a peep sight and a groove aperture from which to choose, both settable to 100 yards at lowest setting. as slide is moved upward the groove on the rear sight base will automatically move to the left to compensate for SPIN DRIFT, that's called the coriallis effect caused by the rotational force imparted by bullit spin. original finish on these rifle was both parkerizing and bluing depending on manufacturer and the model years. all metal parts including sling swivels will have a letter code stamped on them, S for Springfield RI for Rock Island and so on and so forth. original rifles will have a barrel marked same as receiver name, some exceptions are rebarreled rifles and Marine corps rifles which are marked USMC on the barrels for obvious reasons. USMC Sniper versions will be so marked and bolts will be penciled with receiver numbers as they used NM rifles as there sniper base, the original Unertyl scopes were also marked USMC if it is not it is a reproduction or a fake! however you see it. Remington began production of 1903 rifles to help supply logistic's when Springfield armory began tooling up for M1 Garand Production, they were refered to as the 1903 modified, Curiosly Remington did not Produce Proper 03 barrels shortly after production thay modified current tooling of 03A3 barrels to fit the demand of 1903 modified production, the only way to tell is by removing the rear sight collar and examining the ruff machining, as production neared the end the rear bridge on receiver began to change shape, they got taller and had the side ways machined bar that would later become the dovetail for the 03A3 sight base, these are called transition rifles. the rear sights were simplified in design for a couple of reasons, they were more robust and easyer to see in lowlight conditions. they were infact adjustable for both windage and elevation inspite of Current info floating around you know, soldiers who could not figure out elevation and drift (Well maybe if they were AirForce) anyway there are "Collector" rifles and there are "Collectable' rifles, know the difference before you plop down your hard earned cash on an Emotional Purchase, get the facts from a Collector of said weapon and not a Pawn shop esto'mate. I have seen rusted, chopped up, mismatched junk for sale by "Dealers" for top prices because it's OLD and it's a Collector piece. as has been stated they are EXTREMLY ACCURATE Rifles, I have been a Collector and Shooter of these weapons for over 42 years and they will shoot with the best off the shelf rifles available today. but what do I know.
